Income Tax Evasion: A Theoretical Analysis
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Canonical Model: Allingham & Sandmo (1972)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Tax evasion: misreporting tax liability in an 
\emph on
illegal
\emph default
 way
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tax avoidance: exploiting loopholes to minimize tax liability, 
\emph on
without
\emph default
 breaking the law
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A bit of a false taxonomy: Many tax avoidance schemes have never been tested
 in a court, and may well be illegal...
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Classical model is Allingham & Sandmo (JPubE 1972) extended by Yitzhaki
 (1974)
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Builds on Becker's (1968) theory of crime
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Takes true income as given, focus only on decision of what to report to
 the authorities
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Allingham & Sandmo (1972): Setup
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider individual with true income 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 facing linear tax 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 on reported income.
 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The individual chooses to evade an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If they are not caught, their net income is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=W-t\left(W-E\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If they are caught, they pay a penalty rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>t$
\end_inset

 on the evaded amount and have net income
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z=\left(1-t\right)W-\left(\theta-t\right)E
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
They are audited with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Allingham & Sandmo (1972): Solution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individual maximizes expected utility
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\left(1-p\right)U\left(Y\right)+pU\left(Z\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
FOCs yield
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{U^{\prime}\left(Z\right)}{U^{\prime}\left(Y\right)}=\frac{1-p}{p}\frac{t}{\theta-t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Comparative statics:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial E}{\partial\theta} & <0\\
\frac{\partial E}{\partial p} & <0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Allingham & Sandmo (1972) - Yitzhaki (1974)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Effect of tax rate in A-S model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial E}{\partial t}=\underbrace{-\frac{W-E}{1-t}\frac{\partial E}{\partial W}}_{\text{Income Effect}<0}+\underbrace{S}_{\text{Substitution Effect}>0}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Substitution effect (consumption cheaper in unaudited state) seems unintuitive,
 drives ambiguous prediction.
 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Yitzhaki (1974): This is because penalty is on evaded income not evaded
 tax.
 If instead penalty is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta tE$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{U^{\prime}\left(Z\right)}{U^{\prime}\left(Y\right)}=\frac{1-p}{p\left(\theta-1\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No more substitution effect, only income effect
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Chetty (AEJ:Pol 2009) 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
protect
\backslash
textit{
\end_layout

\end_inset

Is the Taxable Income Elasticity Sufficient to Calculate Deadweight Loss?
 The Implications of Evasion and Avoidance
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty (2009): Overview
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How does evasion change how we think about efficiency cost of income taxes?
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Feldstein (1999) argues that elasticity of taxable income is 
\emph on
sufficient statistic
\emph default
 for deadweight loss of income tax.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is this still true when there's evasion?
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Provide simple model to think this through.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
General answer: No, now there are 2 statistics that are jointly sufficient.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty (2009): Benchmark: No Evasion
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals work 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 hours at wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 to maximize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\max_{l}u\left(c,l\right) & =c-\psi\left(l\right)\\
s.t.\;c & =y+\left(1-t\right)wl
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Social Welfare
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left(t\right)=\underbrace{\left\{ y+\left(1-t\right)wl-\psi\left(l\right)\right\} }_{u\left(c^{*},l^{*}\right)}=twl
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Envelope theorem: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{du\left(c^{*},l^{*}\right)}{dt}=\frac{\partial u\left(c^{*},l^{*}\right)}{\partial t}=wl\equiv TI$
\end_inset

 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt} & =-wl+wl+t\frac{d\left[wl\right]}{dt}\\
 & =t\frac{dTI}{dt}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty (2009): Evasion With Real Cost
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Add to the previous model the ability to shelter 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 dollars at convex cost 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(e\right)$
\end_inset

.
 NB 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(e\right)$
\end_inset

 is a real, social cost of evasion
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals choose 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\max_{l,e}u\left(c,l,e\right) & =c-\psi\left(l\right)-g\left(e\right)\\
s.t.\;c & =y+\left(1-t\right)\left(wl-e\right)+e
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Social welfare is now
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left(t\right)=\left\{ y+\left(1-t\right)\left(wl-e\right)+e-\psi\left(l\right)-g\left(e\right)\right\} +t\left(wl-e\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Envelope theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt}=-\left(wl-e\right)+\left(wl-e\right)+t\frac{d\left[wl-e\right]}{dt}=t\frac{dTI}{dt}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Feldstein result survives
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty (2009): Evasion With Transfer Cost
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now add sheltering a la Allingham Sandmo.
 Audit probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(e\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\prime}\left(e\right)>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If caught, pay fine 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(e,t\right)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 private cost 
\begin_inset Formula $z\left(e,t\right)=p\left(e\right)\left[te+F\left(e,t\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 assume strictly convex in 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals choose 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\max_{l,e}u\left(c,l,e\right) & =c-\psi\left(l\right)\\
s.t.\;c & =y+\left(1-t\right)\left(wl-e\right)+e-z\left(e,t\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Social Welfare
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W\left(t\right) & =\left\{ y+\left(1-t\right)\left(wl-e\right)+e-z\left(e,t\right)-\psi\left(l\right)\right\} \\
 & \quad+z\left(e,t\right)+t\left(wl-e\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


