Consumers as Tax Auditors
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Naritomi (2018): Overview
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Kleven et al (2011) shows how important third-party information is for suppressi
ng evasion.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Pomeranz (2015) shows that audit (threats) spill over onto firms connected
 through paper trails.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What happens when there's an increase in the level of third-party information?
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Naritomi (2018) studies the impact of a program in Sao Paulo, Brazil that
 increases third-party information on firms' sales:
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When consumers got a receipt for their purchases, the receipt acted as a
 lottery ticket.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Naritomi (2018): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider an Allingham-Sandmo style model with only government monitoring
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When firms evade an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\overline{Y}-Y$
\end_inset

, they are audited with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If audited, evasion is detected with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Caught evading with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p=a\left(E\right)d$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\prime}\left(E\right)>0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y^{*}=\arg\max_{Y}\pi=\left(\overline{Y}-\tau Y\right)\left(1-p\right)+\left[\left(1-\tau\right)\overline{Y}-\theta\tau\left(\overline{Y}-Y\right)\right]p
\]

\end_inset

with FOC
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[a\left(E\right)+a^{\prime}\left(E\right)\cdot E\right]d\left(1+\theta\right)=1
\]

\end_inset

(same as in Kleven 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 2011)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Naritomi (2018): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now add in consumer monitoring.
 Consumers receive reward 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 share of the tax 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 that firms pay on the transaction.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consumers value the rewards at 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(\alpha\right)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(0\right)=0$
\end_inset

 = government monitoring only.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
with rewards, why might 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(\alpha\right)\neq\alpha$
\end_inset

?
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Firms and consumers can split the surplus from not issuing a receipt.
 Assume firms make take it or leave it offer of a discount 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\overline{y}-y\right)$
\end_inset

 to the consumer.
 Consumer accepts if discount matches the reward 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(\alpha\right)\tau\left(\overline{y}-y\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Naritomi (2018): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 the discount bargaining breaks down and the consumer blows the whistle
 on the firm, triggering an audit.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 consumers probability of detection is now
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{c}\left(N\right)=1-\left(1-d\right)\left(1-\varepsilon\right)^{N}\geq d
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To attempt to strike a deal with a consumer has a fixed cost of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Evasion requires colluding with all consumers (can be relaxed)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Y^{**}=\arg\max_{Y}\pi & =\left(\overline{Y}-\tau Y\right)\left(1-p_{c}\right)+\left[\left(1-\tau\right)\overline{Y}-\theta\tau\left(\overline{Y}-Y\right)\right]p_{c}\\
 & \qquad-\underbrace{\kappa\left(\alpha\right)\tau\left(\overline{Y}-Y\right)}_{\text{discounts}}-\underbrace{\rho N}_{\text{fixed cost}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Naritomi (2018): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now optimal evasion satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[a+a^{\prime}\left(E\right)\cdot E\right]d_{c}\left(1+\theta\right)=1-\kappa\left(\alpha\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The MC (LHS) is higher: 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{c}\geq d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The MB (RHS) is lower: 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(\alpha\right)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Fixed cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho N$
\end_inset

 affects extensive margin (comply fully vs optimal evasion)
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Revenue effects: 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Lottery costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\tau Y^{**}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Revenue increase is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(Y^{**}-Y^{*})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Need 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Y^{**}-Y^{*}\right)/Y^{*}>\alpha/\left(1-\alpha\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Naritomi (2018): Context
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Sao Paulo's 
\emph on
Nota Fiscal Paulista
\emph default
 (NFP) program
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Created in 2007 to increase VAT compliance
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Introduced targeted incentives for consumers to ensure firms report final
 sales
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Targets 2 types of evasion
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
not reporting a transaction at all
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
underreporting the transaction value
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consumers report their SSN at time of purchase.
 SSN attached to receipt sent to tax authority
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Receipts give consumers
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
30% tax rebate
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a lottery ticket for every US$50 spent (prizes from $5 to $500,000)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
