\end_layout

\end_inset

Optimal Tax Administration
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Keen & Slemrod (2017): Overview
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What do policymakers need to know about costs and effectiveness of 
\series bold
\emph on
administrative
\series default
\emph default
 interventions to set them optimally?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Is it better to raise an additional dollar of revenue by raising rates or
 by increasing enforcement?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How big 
\emph on
should
\emph default
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compliance gap
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (gap between tax legally due and tax collected) be? It's not zero so how
 do we know if it's too big or too small?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Show in a simple framework that the key is the 
\emph on
enforcment elasticity of revenue
\emph default
.
 This is the administrative side analog of the elasticity of taxable income.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
optimal administration sets this elasticity equal to ratio of costs and
 revenues (c.f.
 ETI)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
tradeoff between administration and rates rests on balance between ETI and
 enforcement elasticity
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Keen & Slemrod (2017): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Representative individual with quasi-linear preferences:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=x-\psi\left(l\right)+v\left(g\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is consumption; 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is hours worked; and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is public spending
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Public spending financed by linear income tax at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 so individual's BC is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=wl-t\cdot\left(wl-e\right)-c\left(e,\alpha\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is exogenous wage; 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is evaded income; 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are private concealment costs; 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
enforcement parameter
\series default
 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}>0$
\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{e\alpha}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Keen & Slemrod (2017): Individual Choices
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individual's optimal choices satisfy
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
optimal labor supply:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-t\right)w-\psi^{\prime}\left(l\right)=0\quad\Rightarrow l\left(t,w\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
optimal evasion:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t-c_{e}\left(e,\alpha\right)=0\quad\Rightarrow e\left(t,\alpha\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\alpha}<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Keen & Slemrod (2017): Government Choices
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The enforcement technology 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 has administrative costs 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(\alpha\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Government's BC is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g+a\left(\alpha\right)=t\cdot\left(wl-e\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Makes social welfare
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left(t,\alpha\right)=wl-t\cdot\left(wl-e\right)-c\left(e,\alpha\right)-\psi\left(l\right)+v\left(t\cdot\left(wl-e\right)-a\left(\alpha\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Maximizing and using the Envelope Theorem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{t}=-z+v^{\prime}\cdot\left(z+tz_{t}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z\left(t,\alpha\right)=wl\left(t,w\right)-e\left(t,\alpha\right)$
\end_inset

 is taxable income.
 Rearranging
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{t}{1-t}=\left(\frac{v^{\prime}-1}{v^{\prime}}\right)\frac{1}{E\left(z,1-t\right)}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(z,1-t\right)$
\end_inset

 is the famous ETI
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Keen & Slemrod (2017): Optimal Administration
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What about the optimal choice of enforcement 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

?
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{\alpha}=-c_{\alpha}+v^{\prime}\cdot\left(tz_{\alpha}-a_{\alpha}\right)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can do a similar rearranging.
 Define the 
\emph on
adjusted marginal cost - revenue ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\equiv\frac{\alpha\left(c_{\alpha}/v^{\prime}\right)+\alpha a_{\alpha}}{tz}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now you can rearrange to see that the optimal administration satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(z,\alpha\right)=\phi
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(z,\alpha\right)$
\end_inset

 is the elasticity of taxable income wrt enforcement
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Keen & Slemrod (2017): Balancing Policy & Administration
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If enforcement is constrained to be low, should we respond by having higher
 tax rates? or lower?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
higher tax rates would offset the losses from weak administration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But lower tax rates would reduce the loss from high evasion
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The answer depends on whether policy and administration are 
\emph on
strategic complements or substitutes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{t\alpha}=-\underbrace{\left(v^{\prime}-1\right)}_{>0}e_{\alpha}-v^{\prime}te_{t\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Proposition: A sufficient condition for strategic complementary (
\begin_inset Formula $dt/d\alpha>0$
\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t\alpha}\leq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Keen & Slemrod (2017): Balancing Policy & Administration
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Should we raise a marginal dollar from tax rates or enforcement?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the following thought experiment: Do a balanced budget reform that
 increase 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 by a tiny bit 
\begin_inset Formula $d\alpha$
\end_inset

 and simultaneously offsets this with a tax rate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\frac{dt}{d\alpha}\right|_{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Does welfare go up?
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dW=W_{t}\left.\frac{dt}{d\alpha}\right|_{g}+W_{\alpha}\gtrless0?
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Proposition: Marginal revenue should come from tax rate increase iff
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{E\left(z,\alpha\right)-\frac{\alpha a_{\alpha}}{tz}}{1-\frac{t}{1-t}E\left(z,1-t\right)}>\frac{\alpha c_{\alpha}}{tz}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shows how to combine sufficient statistics to guide policy.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Basri, Felix, Hanna & Olken (AER 2020) 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
protect
\backslash
textit{
\end_layout

\end_inset

Tax Administration vs.
 Tax Rates: Evidence from Corporate Taxation in Indonesia
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Basri et al (2020): Overview
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We've seen several papers now on how to use enforcement techniques to improve
 compliance and raise revenue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We also saw one paper (Best et al.
 2015) on how to use policy design (bases, rates) to improve compliance
 and raise revenue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Say that you have to choose between improving tax administration and improving
 tax compliance.
 How should you think about the tradeoff between the two?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This paper:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Apply Keen & Slemrod (2017) framework to Indonesia
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Leverage quasi-experimental variation from admin reform and from tax rate
 reform to estimate key elasticities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug elasticities into the sufficient statistics framework to quantify tradeoffs
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Basri et al (2020): Context
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Study corporate income tax administered by Directorate General of Taxation
 (DGT)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Big administrative reforms started in 2002
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
largest 200 firms' admin moved to centralized Large Taxpayer Office (LTO)
 in Jakarta.
 Several hundred taxpayers in each region 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 handled by Medium Taxpayer Offices (MTOs).
 Focus on big wave of MTOs created in 2007.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Offices restructured.
 pre-reform offices organized by tax type.
 Post-reform each taxpayer assigned to an office and a single contact person.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Corporate income tax rate reform in 2009.
 Pre-reform there was a progressive tax with MTR increasing in taxable profit.
 Post-reform tax schedule depends on gross income, and rate is flat with
 discounts:
\end_layout

\end_deeper
